solutions.content:
Funny problem and we might be tempted to solve it in several ways, but the one I think might be the most convenient consists of few relatively easy steps:
* we will iterate through each cell until we find the first bit of land;
* once there, we will "colour" all the cells of the same first island in a different way to mark them as different from the second island and add them to a queue;
* after having finished mapping all the elements in the first island, we will run a search from there to try and reach the second island in the shortest amount of steps.

We will use a DFS to colour/mark all the elements of the first island and, as it is often the case in order to efficiently find the minimum number of steps, a BFS to move from the first to the second island.

Now, to get started, let's first of all declare a few instance variables:
* `qLen` will store the length of our queue;
* `maxX` and `maxY` will store the value of the maximum column and row index we can get, respectively;
* `grid` will contain our initial input;
* `q` is the queue of coordinate pairs we will use in our BFS logic.

In the main function, we will also declare `res` with an initial value of `-1` (since we will count the distance betweeen both islands, but without the destination itself, so we will have to count one less step for that) and then assign the proper values to `grid`, `maxX` and `maxY`.

Next, we will try to loop with `cy` and `cx` through each cell in `grid` and, as soon as we find a land cell (ie: `grid[cy][cx] == 1`), we will:
* call `dfs` on the two current coordinates;
* run our BFS search from there.

Now, focusing on the first step, our helper function `dfs` will take two coordinates `x` and `y` and:
* mark the current cell `grid[y][x]` as visited with a value of `-1` (but, really, it could be anything which is not in `[0, 1]`);
* check in every direction if we would not go out of boundaries and if it still a land cell (ie: with value `== 1`) and if so, we will call `dfs` recursively on that bit of land;
* add the current coordinates `x` and `y` to `q`;
* increase `qLen` by `1`.

Our BFS logic will run when we have already finished marking/colouring all of the first island as visited and put all of its cells in `q`, so we will run `while` `q` is not empty (ie: `qLen != 0`) and:
* do a level traversal, checking the first `qLen` elements currently in `q` and:
    * extract the `x` and `y` coordinates of the current node (ie: `q.front()`);
    * pop the current node out of `q`;
    * if we have reached the other island (ie: `grid[y][x] == 1`), we will `return` `res`;
    * if not, we will use a similar logic to check every adjacent cell that is not part of the first island (ie: with value `!= -1`) and, if so:
        * push its coordinates into `q`;
        * mark it as visited (same colour of the first island to simplify the logic - it will do just fine) if it a sea square (ie: value `== 0`)
* increase `res` by `1` (we are now taking an extra step);
* restore `qLen` to be the current length of `q`. 

The end of our core logic still has to have a `return` statement we will never reach, since we are guaranteed to have always two separate islands. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity:. $$O(n)$$

# Code
```cpp
class Solution {
    int qLen = 0, maxX, maxY;
    vector<vector<int>> grid;
    queue<pair<int, int>> q;
    void dfs(int x, int y) {
        // marking the current cell as visited
        grid[y][x] = -1;
        // moving east
        if (x < maxX && grid[y][x + 1] == 1) dfs(x + 1, y);
        // moving south
        if (y < maxY && grid[y + 1][x] == 1) dfs(x, y + 1);
        // moving west
        if (x && grid[y][x - 1] == 1) dfs(x - 1, y);
        // moving north
        if (y && grid[y - 1][x] == 1) dfs(x, y - 1);
        // storing the current cell as belonging to the first island
        q.push({x, y}), qLen++;
    }
public:
    int shortestBridge(vector<vector<int>> &tmp) {
        // support variables
        int res = -1;
        // populating instance variables
        swap(tmp, grid);
        maxX = grid[0].size() - 1, maxY = grid.size() - 1;
        // parsing grid to find the first bit of land
        for (int cy = 0; cy <= maxY; cy++) {
            for (int cx = 0; cx <= maxX; cx++) {
                if (grid[cy][cx]) {
                    // marking the first island and adding its tiles to q
                    dfs(cx, cy);
                    // looking for the closest island with a BFS
                    while (qLen) {
                        // level traversal
                        while (qLen--) {
                            // extracting the current front of q
                            auto [x, y] = q.front();
                            q.pop();
                            // other island found!
                            if (grid[y][x] == 1) return res;
                            // moving east and marking is as added
                            if (x < maxX && grid[y][x + 1] != -1) {
                                q.push({x + 1, y});
                                if (!grid[y][x + 1]) grid[y][x + 1] = -1;
                            }
                            // moving south and marking is as added
                            if (y < maxY && grid[y + 1][x] != -1) {
                                q.push({x, y + 1});
                                if (!grid[y + 1][x]) grid[y + 1][x] = -1;
                            }
                            // moving west and marking is as added
                            if (x && grid[y][x - 1] != -1) {
                                q.push({x - 1, y});
                                if (!grid[y][x - 1]) grid[y][x - 1] = -1;
                            }
                            // moving north and marking is as added
                            if (y && grid[y - 1][x] != -1) {
                                q.push({x, y - 1});
                                if (!grid[y - 1][x]) grid[y - 1][x] = -1;
                            }
                        }
                        // preparing for the next pass
                        res++, qLen = q.size();
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

