solutions.content:
**Approach**
The solution is based on the fact that there are only two island components in the grid.

**Step1.  Find Island1**
In the first step, we would run a DFS to find the first island and would mark all the components of that island as visited.  
Simulataneously , add all the components of island1 to a queue (It would be used later in Step2) .

if(visited[i][j] == 0), it means grid[i][j] is visited and is a component of island1.
if(visited[i][j]  == -1), it means grid[i][j] is not visited. It also means that either grid[i][j] == 0 or  it is part of second island.


**Step2. Find Shortest Distance From Island1 to Island2**
Since, The island 2 can be reached by multiple paths/components of Island1. Thus, to find the shortest distance, we need to run BFS from all the components of island1.
Queue<int[]> ue stores the indices of all the components of island1.


In the BFS traversal, go through all the valid neighbours of each component ->
if neighbour is 0, i.e grid[i][j] == 0 We still have not reached Island2.  Hence, visited[i][j] = visited[x][y] + 1 .
else if neighbour is 1 ie grid[i][j] == 1, It must be a part of Island2. (We have already traversed all the components of island1).  
It should be the shortest distance between island1 and Island2. Hence, return visited[x][y].

*Please feel free to ask any doubts. Also, Please upvote if you find it useful.*




```
class Solution {
    int[] rows = {-1 , 0 , 1 , 0} ;
    int[] cols = {0 , 1 , 0, -1} ;
     Queue<int[]> ue = new LinkedList<>() ;

    public int shortestBridge(int[][] grid) {
        int n = grid.length ;
        int[][] visited = new int[n][n] ;

        for(int[] arr : visited)
            Arrays.fill(arr , -1) ;
        int count = 0 ;

        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            for(int j = 0 ; j < n ; j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == 1 && count == 0){
                    dfs(grid , n , i , j , visited) ;
                    count ++ ;
                }
            }
        }


        while(! ue.isEmpty() ){
            int[] arr = ue.peek();
            ue.poll() ;

            int x = arr[0] ;
            int y = arr[1] ;

            for(int k = 0 ; k < 4 ; k++){
                int i = x + rows[k] ;
                int j = y + cols[k] ;

                if(i >= 0 && j >= 0 && i < n && j < n && visited[i][j] == -1){
                    if(grid[i][j] == 1)
                        return visited[x][y] ;
                    else {
                       visited[i][j] = visited[x][y] + 1 ;
                        ue.add(new int[]{i , j} );
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return -1;

    }

    private void dfs(int[][] grid , int n , int i , int j , int[][] visited){
        visited[i][j] = 0 ;
        ue.add(new int[]{i , j} );

        for(int k = 0 ; k < 4 ; k++){
            int x = i + rows[k] ;
            int y = j + cols[k] ;

            if(x >= 0 && y >= 0 && x <n && y < n && grid[x][y] == 1 
               && visited[x][y] == -1)
                dfs(grid , n , x , y , visited) ;
        }


    }


}
```

