The idea is to use a stack to store alphabets with non-zero counts. In the meantime a dictionary records counts for each alphabet. Every time it will pop one letter into output and decrease counts by 1. If this letter has more counts available it will be put into the other stack. Repeat until stack is empty. Running time is ~60ms and 91% faster. 

```
class Solution:
    def sortString(self, s: str) -> str:
        c = collections.Counter(s)
        stack= []
        for ch in string.ascii_lowercase[::-1]:
            if c[ch] > 0:
                stack.append(ch)
        res = ""
        while stack:
            temp = []
            while stack:
                ch = stack.pop()
                res += ch
                if c[ch] > 1:
                    c[ch] -= 1
                    temp.append(ch)
            stack = temp[:]
        return res
```

